The problem requires finding \(P(Y_7 < 27.3)\), where \(Y_7\) is the seventh order statistic in a sample of eight independent observations from a continuous distribution with a 70th percentile of \(\pi_{0.7} = 27.3\).

For a continuous distribution, \(P(X < 27.3) = 0.7\) for any single observation. The event \(Y_7 < 27.3\) is equivalent to at least seven observations being less than 27.3. Let \(N\) be the number of observations less than 27.3, which follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 8\) and \(p = 0.7\).

Thus,  
\[P(Y_7 < 27.3) = P(N \geq 7) = P(N = 7) + P(N = 8).\]

Calculate each probability:  
\[P(N = 7) = \binom{8}{7} \cdot (0.7)^7 \cdot (0.3)^1 = 8 \cdot (0.7)^7 \cdot 0.3,\]  
\[P(N = 8) = \binom{8}{8} \cdot (0.7)^8 \cdot (0.3)^0 = 1 \cdot (0.7)^8 \cdot 1 = (0.7)^8.\]

Compute the powers:  
\[(0.7)^7 = 0.0823543,\]  
\[(0.7)^8 = 0.05764801.\]

Then,  
\[P(N = 7) = 8 \cdot 0.0823543 \cdot 0.3 = 0.19765032,\]  
\[P(N = 8) = 0.05764801.\]

Summing these:  
\[P(N \geq 7) = 0.19765032 + 0.05764801 = 0.25529833.\]

Rounding to three decimal places (as the input 27.3 has three significant figures and the probability calculation is reasonably rounded), the result is 0.255.

