The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), where \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)), \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters. The wavelength is \(300 \, \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\).

First, compute the energy for one photon:  
\[ E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{h c}{\lambda} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}. \]

Then, for one mole of photons:  
\[ E_{\text{mole}} = E_{\text{photon}} \times N_A = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}. \]

Convert to kJ/mol (since \(1 \, \text{kJ} = 1000 \, \text{J}\)):  
\[ E_{\text{mole}} = \frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399.0 \, \text{kJ/mol}. \]

Rounded to three significant figures (based on the wavelength input of 300 nm), the energy is \(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

