Solution: The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) of a random sample of size 12 from a uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has a mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{12}\). The standard error of \(\bar{X}\) is \(\sigma_{\bar{X}} = \sqrt{\frac{\sigma^2}{n}} = \sqrt{\frac{1/12}{12}} = \frac{1}{12}\).

By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed. The probability \(P\left(\frac{1}{2} \leq \bar{X} \leq \frac{2}{3}\right)\) is approximated by standardizing the bounds to z-scores. The lower bound \(\frac{1}{2} = 0.5\) gives:
\[
z_{\text{lower}} = \frac{0.5 - 0.5}{1/12} = 0.
\]
The upper bound \(\frac{2}{3} \approx 0.6667\) gives:
\[
z_{\text{upper}} = \frac{0.6667 - 0.5}{1/12} = \frac{0.1667}{0.08333} \approx 2,
\]
which is exactly 2 when using fractions: \(\frac{2/3 - 1/2}{1/12} = \frac{1/6}{1/12} = 2\).

The probability is \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\) for a standard normal variable \(Z\). Using the standard normal distribution:
- \(P(Z \leq 2) \approx 0.97725\),
- \(P(Z \leq 0) = 0.5\),
- \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = 0.97725 - 0.5 = 0.47725\).

