Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds 8 after 10 triples, with each drug having a success probability of 0.7 per use. Since each triple assigns one patient to each drug, each drug is used 10 times independently.

Let \(S_i\) be the number of successes for drug \(i\), where \(S_i \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)\) for \(i = 1, 2, 3\). The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds 8 is \(P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8)\), which is equivalent to \(1 - P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8)\).

Since the \(S_i\) are independent and identically distributed:
\[
P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8) = P(S_1 \leq 8) \cdot P(S_2 \leq 8) \cdot P(S_3 \leq 8) = [P(S \leq 8)]^3,
\]
where \(S \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)\).

First, compute \(P(S \leq 8)\):
\[
P(S \leq 8) = 1 - P(S = 9) - P(S = 10).
\]
\[
P(S = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \cdot (0.7)^9 \cdot 0.3 \approx 10 \cdot 0.040353607 \cdot 0.3 = 0.121060821,
\]
\[
P(S = 10) = (0.7)^{10} \approx 0.0282475249,
\]
\[
P(S = 9) + P(S = 10) \approx 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459,
\]
\[
P(S \leq 8) \approx 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541.
\]

Then:
\[
[P(S \leq 8)]^3 \approx (0.8506916541)^3 \approx 0.615625.
\]

Thus:
\[
P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8) = 1 - 0.615625 = 0.384375.
\]

Rounded to three significant figures, the probability is 0.384.

